[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In this video, I\'ll be looking at Higgsfield Games, which is powered by Claude\'s Fable 5, where you can create a game with just one prompt. It\'s pretty nuts. Okay, let\'s get into it. This video will be a bit rough around the edges, and it\'s something that I don\'t usually talk about. When I first heard'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that Higgsfield released a Higgsfield Games, I was a bit skeptical, but then I did actually start playing around with it, and I\'ve been really surprised with what you can do. It is powered by Claude\'s Fable 5 model, and I\'ve been seeing some absolutely wild things that'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can create with that. Now, what Higgsfield have done is they\'ve just streamlined the whole process and made it so that anyone can create a game. Now, these games aren\'t the craziest games you\'ve ever seen, but I\'ve been very impressed with the creativity that'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'people have been putting into them. And I actually made around 20 games in under an hour. So, I\'ve actually left the links to the games I\'ve created in a document down below if you do want to test them out. So, if we jump straight into Higgsfield Games, you can create'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your game in two different ways. You can create your games in Claude using the Higgsfield MCP, and if you do want to do this, all you have to do is copy this URL and paste it into Claude, and then it will add Higgsfield as a connector. So, then when you\'re in Claude and you'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'say, "I want to create a game about something," it will then recognize to use the Higgsfield MCP to create that game. But, this will use your Claude credits. I\'ve been making all of my games using the supercomputer, which is built into Higgsfield. What\'s great is'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they\'ll give you a few different game genres to pick from from shooter, platformer, novella, hyper-casual, racing, and horror. Then, as you can see, it\'s using Fable 5 model there. You can switch these genres off if you just want to use the prompt. You get a few'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different art styles to choose from, or you can prompt your own. And with the settings, you can change your different environment settings. And what\'s awesome is you can add multiplayer into these games. So, you\'ll be able to send this link to your friends and play together.'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And down here, we can see games made by other users, and I\'ll be testing some of these out shortly. So, we have everything from first-person shooters to god simulators, a really cool gesture game which uses your webcam to actually'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'track your hand movements, and tons of other ones. And you can see how many people have been playing them. So, this Strike Protocol one, at the time of recording, has been played over 10,000 times, which is pretty wild, as it only just got released. There\'s so many games'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to test out, so I\'ll just quickly check out Strike Protocol. Now, see, you can see play with friends, but I\'ll just go to deploy, and you can have an online match. So, as you can see, I can walk around, can jump. It\'s pretty'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clean-looking. Aim down the sights. Yep, got him. Reload. Yeah, I think it looks really nice for a game that was probably made in half an hour. I can imagine if you just played'

[02:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with your mates, it would be a bit good bit of fun. Now, it\'s no Halo, but, you know, this was a game made with AI, so yeah, five-kill streak. I\'ll leave it at that. Now, let\'s check out the Gesture'

[02:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Synth game. Now, this one\'s really interesting, as it actually uses your webcam and tracks your hands to create music. Okay, so you can see me on the camera, and you\'ll see it\'s tracking my hands.'

[02:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And it\'s doing a really good job of the tracking, actually. Then, if you put your fingers together, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; and then, if you move across the scene, &gt;&gt; [music]'

[03:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; that\'s pretty cool. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; I think that\'s pretty awesome. And you'

[03:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can change the scale as well. Change the root. You can change the wave. That\'s pretty crazy. And you\'ll see, it'

[03:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'doesn\'t even work when I use my other fingers, as it\'s just instructed to use my index finger and my thumb. It might seem a bit useless, but it is'

[03:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kind of fun to be able to interact and create music this way. I can see kids really enjoying this kind of thing. In this god simulator, you actually get to build your community and go to war with other communities as well. So, I'

[04:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'did actually have a game earlier where there was two other people online and they just started sending troops to my community and destroyed all of my houses. Now, it\'s not going to be as in-depth as say Age of Empires, but I still think you could probably have a'

[04:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bit of fun with this. And this is pretty crazy. I\'ve just noticed a game on here was one that I just created like a couple of hours ago. For this one, I actually wanted to create a game with physics based in it. So, I might as well show you and we can check it out. So,'

[04:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s called Gravity Wells. And if we play it, the idea is to get your probe through the rivers of gravity and to its destination. So, if I start on this one, so as you can see, it\'s kind of like an'

[04:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Angry Birds style where you\'re dragging the thing and you can see the trajectory of where it\'s going to go. And I need to get to the right side where that kind of glowing icon is. So, if I let go,'

[04:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; oh, no. I needed a little bit more power on that one. So, you can retry. It\'s got some nice chill music as well. &gt;&gt; [snorts]'

[05:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] &gt;&gt; Nope. Again, I am not good at this. Drifted into the void. Yes, finally. Gate reached. And now on this one, you can see there\'s two'

[05:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'gravity wells, so it does amp up the difficulty the further you get into it. So close.'

[05:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Yes. I had no idea people were actually playing the game I created a couple of hours ago, which is pretty awesome. So, talking about that Gravity Wells game, I\'ll show you how it was made. So, all I did within Hexfield Games using the'

[05:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'supercomputer, I didn\'t use any of these preset genres. Literally, all I put into the prompt was, "Can you create a game about physics?" And here is the breakdown of what Claude Fable 5 went through to create the game. So, as you'

[05:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can see here, it made the game in just over 25 minutes, but it actually does a lot in the background. So, you can see on the right here all of the different assets it created from the sound effects, &gt;&gt; [music]'

[06:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; the icons and the artwork that the game uses. So, as you can see on the left here, this is all of the thinking that Claude Fable 5 is doing. It\'s doing all of these processes and running loads of tasks to get this game ready. And yeah, there\'s just a lot going on behind the'

[06:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scenes. And then when it finishes, it will give you this link at the bottom where you can open that game in a web browser and play it for yourself. And what I really like is that they show you how many credits it used to create the game. So, if you click on usage, it will'

[06:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'show you how many image credits it used, the text credits through Claude, video credits and audio credits. So, all up it cost just over 210 credits, which is around two Seedance two videos. And to get a game that you can actually play'

[06:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and have a bit of fun, I think it\'s well worth it. And as I was recording this, another one of my games has just finished. Okay, so let\'s check it out. And it says you can choose your vehicle, keyboard speedway. You can choose different tracks. Oh, I\'ll just stick on'

[07:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that one. Okay, ready. Reminds me a lot of Micro Machines. Oh, these little things slow you down. I see. So, it\'s very very simple, but it\'s still pretty cool to generate these kind of games. I even added myself into'

[07:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a game as well. So, you can upload images of yourself to use in your game. And in this one here, I actually have already created an element of myself, so I selected that. And in these examples here, I created a novella and a horror'

[07:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'game. So, the way these games work is that you kind of go through a story and you get alternative endings depending on which story path you choose. And in this simple arcade game here, it turns myself into a really cool little cartoon'

[07:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'character. It\'s deceptively simple, but it\'s one of those games that the further you get, the higher the points you get. What\'s cool is you can play on your mobile phone if you want to. So, this was a perfect game to play on my phone as all I had to do was tap on the screen'

[07:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to jump and slide, and it worked really well. I made some really interesting first-person shooter games. So, in this one called Chrono Echo, so when you die in this game, you respawn and the ghost'

[08:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of your previous life still runs through the actions of before to help you get through the levels. So, I\'ll show you what I mean. Now, this one is a bit broken as the bullets aren\'t in the middle where the reticle is, but I can'

[08:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kind of get around that. So, stand on the glowing plate until the loop ends. So, as you can see, the door opens when I stand on that plate, and I kind of have to wait for this time to go down before I die, and then my second'

[08:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'character can then pass through that door. So, as you can see, that\'s a ghost of me from the previous play-through, and when it stands on that plate, I\'ll be able to go through this door and progress in the level. Cool. So, I can go through.'

[08:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Oh. There\'s some enemies in here. So, you get the gist of it. Each time you die, you\'re helping yourself progress through the level, which I think is a really interesting concept for a game that was made in like 30'

[08:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'minutes. And in this game called Veridian Zero, we can restore the life. So, I have this little gun. We can restore the greenery to the land. I can grow flowers, and I can actually grow walls as well.'

[09:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, I can hide behind them. And here\'s a really interesting example of a game that Higgsfield posted. So, as you can see, they uploaded a research paper on the behavior of chimpanzees,'

[09:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which was over 900 pages long, and they asked Claude to make a game from it. Now, I haven\'t tried this myself, but it seems like a pretty wild way on how to create a game. Now, I know these games are pretty basic, but I think it\'s just'

[09:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really interesting that we\'ve got to this point now where we can just type in one simple prompt and get a playable game out of it. I\'m sure all of you guys could create better games than what I\'ve made. I would actually love it if you do create a game, then share your link down'

